message.content: We want to find the value(s) of $x$ for which $f(x) = f^{-1}(x)$. Letting $f(x) = y$, this means $y = f^{-1}(x)$. Therefore we have \[y = f^{-1}(x) \iff f(y) = f(f^{-1}(x)).\]Since $f(x) = 3x-8$, we substitute to get \[f(y) = f(f^{-1}(x)) \iff 3y-8 = f^{-1}(x).\]Since $y = f(x) = 3x-8$, we have \[f^{-1}(x) = 3(3x-8)-8 = 9x-32.\]Therefore \[3y-8=9x-32,\]or $9x = 3y+24$. But we also have $y = 3x-8$, so $9x=9x+8$, or $8=0$. This equation is never true, so there are $\boxed{\text{no values}}$ of $x$ for which $f(x) = f^{-1}(x)$.
